Introduction to Dimensionality Reduction

The training session began with an introduction to Dimensionality Reduction, an important data preprocessing technique used in Machine Learning to reduce the number of input features while preserving the most important information. Learned that high-dimensional datasets often increase computational complexity, training time, and the risk of overfitting.

The trainer explained that dimensionality reduction simplifies datasets, improves model efficiency, and helps visualize complex data without significantly affecting prediction performance.

Discussed real-world applications such as image processing, facial recognition, text mining, bioinformatics, recommendation systems, and financial data analysis.

Understanding High-Dimensional Data

Studied the concept of high-dimensional datasets, where a dataset contains a large number of features or variables.

Learned that high-dimensional data may lead to:

Increased computational cost.
Longer model training time.
Higher memory usage.
Difficulty in data visualization.
Increased risk of overfitting.
Reduced model performance.

Discussed examples of datasets containing hundreds or thousands of features, such as image pixels and gene expression data.

Curse of Dimensionality

Received a detailed explanation of the Curse of Dimensionality.

Learned that as the number of features increases:

Data becomes sparse.
Distance calculations become less meaningful.
Machine Learning algorithms require more training data.
Model performance may decrease.

The trainer explained why reducing unnecessary features improves model efficiency and generalization.

Feature Selection vs Feature Extraction

Studied the difference between Feature Selection and Feature Extraction.

Feature Selection

Learned that feature selection chooses only the most relevant existing features without modifying them.

Examples discussed:

Filter Methods
Wrapper Methods
Embedded Methods
Feature Extraction

Learned that feature extraction creates new features by combining existing variables while retaining the most useful information.

Examples:

Principal Component Analysis (PCA)
Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA)

Compared the advantages and applications of both approaches.

Introduction to Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

Received an introduction to Principal Component Analysis (PCA), one of the most popular dimensionality reduction techniques.

Learned that PCA transforms correlated features into a smaller number of new variables called Principal Components.

Studied the objectives of PCA:

Reduce feature dimensions.
Preserve maximum variance.
Remove redundant information.
Improve computational efficiency.
Simplify data visualization.
Working of PCA

Studied the step-by-step process of PCA.

Learned that PCA:

Standardizes the dataset.
Computes the covariance matrix.
Calculates eigenvalues and eigenvectors.
Identifies principal components.
Selects components with the highest explained variance.
Projects the original data onto the new feature space.

Understood how PCA compresses information while minimizing data loss.

Explained Variance

Learned about Explained Variance, which indicates how much information is retained by each principal component.

Studied:

Individual Explained Variance
Cumulative Explained Variance

Discussed how explained variance helps determine the optimal number of principal components.

